To draw a chessboard in LaTeX, you can make use of the "tikz" package which provides an easy-to-use interface for producing graphics in LaTeX. Here's a simple LaTeX code snippet that creates a 8x8 chessboard with the given FEN position:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric, arrows}
\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
    % Define the color of the squares
    \definecolor{lightSquareColor}{RGB}{248, 248, 222}
    \definecolor{darkSquareColor}{RGB}{145, 145, 141}

    % Define the size of the squares
    \pgfmathsetmacro{\squareSize}{0.5}

    % Draw the chessboard
    \foreach \x in {0, ..., 7} {
        \foreach \y in {0, ..., 7} {
            \draw[thick]
                (\y*\squareSize,\x*\squareSize)
                ++(-0.5*\squareSize,0)
                ++(0,-0.5*\squareSize)
                ++(0.5*\squareSize,-0.5*\squareSize);

            % Draw a small border for better visual distinction
            \pgfmathsetmacro{\innerSquareSize}{\squareSize - 0.04}

            \draw[thin]
                (\y*\innerSquareSize-0.05, \x*\innerSquareSize-0.05)
                ++(\innerSquareSize, 0)
                ++(0, \innerSquareSize)
                ++(-\innerSquareSize, 0)
                ++(0, -\innerSquareSize);
        }
    }

    % Draw the pieces
    % Replace "R" with "K", "Q" with "Q", "B" with "B", "N" with "N", "P" with "P"
    % and "r" with "k", "q" with "q", "b" with "b", "n" with "n", "p" with "p"
    % to draw the pieces of the current FEN position
    \node at (3.5, 3.5) {R};
    \node at (4.5, 3.5) {N};
    \node at (3.5, 4.5) {B};
    \node at (4.5, 4.5) {Q};
    \node at (3.5, 5.5) {K};
    \node at (4.5, 5.5) {N};
    \node at (3.5, 6.5) {B};
    \node at (4.5, 6.5) {R};

    \node at (3.5+2*\squareSize, 3.5) {r};
    \node at (4.5+2*\squareSize, 3.5) {n};
    \node at (3.5+2*\squareSize, 4.5) {b};
    \node at (4.5+2*\squareSize, 4.5) {q};
    \node at (3.5+2*\squareSize, 5.5) {k};
    \node at (4.5+2*\squareSize, 5.5) {n};
    \node at (3.5+2*\squareSize, 6.5) {b};
    \node at (4.5+2*\squareSize, 6.5) {r};
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

This code will draw an empty chessboard and place the specified pieces on it in standard coordinates from Algebraic notation (e.g., `R1c2` for Rook on square c2). Note that you might need to adjust `\squareSize` to fit your requirements.

The pieces are placed according to their standard positions in chess: 

- King (`K`) and king (`k`) are placed in central squares.
- Queen (`Q`) and queen (`q`) are placed on squares adjacent to kings.
- Bishop (`B`) and bishop (`b`) are placed on squares diagonally adjacent to queen.
- Knight (`N`) and knight (`n`) are placed on squares adjacent to bishop.
- Rook (`R`) and rook (`r`) are placed on squares adjacent to knights.

Make sure to adjust this according to your specific FEN position and coordinate system.

If you want to include an interactive version of this chessboard in your LaTeX document that allows players to interact directly with a piece or a move in the board, you can use a library like `luatexja` or `xparse` to allow for user input and respond to commands accordingly. This topic goes beyond the scope of a simple LaTeX code snippet and requires more advanced programming skills in Lua or other languages supported by LaTeX like TeX macros or TeXLive scripts.

Please note that complex interactions or animations may require a more advanced setup and additional software packages like `pgfplots` or `pstricks`.

